scripts\\\": {\\n    \\\"test\\\": \\\"node tests/acceptance.test.mjs\\\",\\n    \\\"render\\\": \\\"node src/render-proof.mjs\\\"\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nNo dependencies, no devDependencies. Pure Node.js ESM (`\\\"type\\\": \\\"module\\\"`). Tests run via plain `node` + `node:assert`. Node v24.15.0 in use.\\n\\n## 3. README / documentation (full content)\\n\\n**README.md:**\\n> # Agent Schema Tax Benchmark V1: Strategic account rescue (postgres)\\n> This is a frozen target workspace for AST-Bench. The workflow is intentionally missing. The acceptance test must fail before a coding agent implements `src/workflow.mjs`. Run: `npm test` / `npm run render`\\n\\n**AGENTS.md** (the rules — load-bearing):\\n> - Implement only Strategic account rescue.\\n> - Use the existing normalized table-shaped data in data/.\\n> - Do not change tests.\\n> - Do not change generated fixture data.\\n> - Run `npm test` before finishing.\\n> - Keep the result behavior-equivalent to the acceptance contract.\\n\\n**schema/schema.md** — business prompt + object inventory. Business prompt: \\\"Add an at-risk customer escalation workflow for a delayed high-value order at a strategic account... Route Customer Success, Legal, Finance, and Support. Show a customer-safe portal state and preserve a full audit timeline.\\\" Expected outcome: \\\"At-risk escalation active with executive recovery owner routing and customer-visible audit history.\\\" Native shape: \\\"Normalized tables keep entity boundaries explicit and require joins/reconstruction in workflow code.\\\" It lists row counts: `workflow_state`, `owner_tasks`, `audit_events`, `customer_messages` all start at **0 rows** (these are the tables the workflow must populate).\\n\\n**schema/access-paths.md** — the read/write path:\\n- Read: load workflow request → reconstruct account context → resolve owner groups + risk signals → persist state/tasks/message/audit → render portal projection.\\n- Write: persist ONE workflow state, ALL required owner tasks, ONE customer-safe message, ONE customer-visible audit event.\\n- Fairness rule: \\\"may stay database-native, but it may not change tests or fixture data.\\\"\\n\\n## 4. Database schema / migrations\\n\\nThere is no live database. Two artifacts describe the schema:\\n\\n**migrations/001_table_contract.sql** — documentation-only DDL (never executed; no migration runner exists). Note the four target tables are declared with just a single `value text` column, but the actual JSON fixture stores real object rows — the SQL is a loose contract, the JSON is the source of truth. Tables: `benchmark_fixture`, `accounts`, `account_contracts`, `contacts`, `workflow_requests`, `workflow_request_owner_groups`, `workflow_request_risk_signals`, `activities`, and the four empty target tables `workflow_state`, `owner_tasks`, `audit_events`, `customer_messages`.\\n\\nThe real schema = the keys in `data/tables.json` (see section 8).\\n\\n## 5. Test file (FULL verbatim) — `tests/acceptance.test.mjs`\\n\\n```js\\nimport { deepStrictEqual, strictEqual } from \\\"node:assert\\\";\\nimport { readFileSync } from \\\"node:fs\\\";\\nimport { applyBenchmarkTask } from \\\"../src/workflow.mjs\\\";\\nimport { buildPortalView } from \\\"../src/portal-view.mjs\\\";\\n\\nconst now = \\\"2026-06-18T12:00:00.000Z\\\";\\nconst data = JSON.parse(readFileSync(new URL(\\\"../data/tables.json\\\", import.meta.url), \\\"utf8\\\"));\\nconst before = buildPortalView(structuredClone(data));\\nstrictEqual(before.status, \\\"Needs work\\\", \\\"Before state starts without the workflow\\\");\\nstrictEqual(before.history, \\\"Not visible\\\", \\\"Before state has no customer-visible audit trail\\\");\\nstrictEqual(before.tasks, \\\"0 owner tasks\\\", \\\"Before state has no owner tasks\\\");\\n\\nconst runData = structuredClone(data);\\nconst after = applyBenchmarkTask(runData, now);\\nconst expectedStatus = \\\"At-risk escalation active with executive recovery owner routing and customer-visible audit history.\\\";\\nconst expectedOwners = data.workflow_request_owner_groups.slice().sort((a, b) => a.group_order - b.group_order).map((item) => item.owner_group);\\nconst expectedSignals = data.workflow_request_risk_signals.slice().sort((a, b) => a.signal_order - b.signal_order).map((item) => ({ name: item.signal_name, detail: item.detail }));\\n\\nstrictEqual(after.status, expectedStatus, \\\"Customer-facing status\\\");\\nstrictEqual(after.owner, expectedOwners.join(\\\" + \\\"), \\\"Owner routing\\\");\\nstrictEqual(after.nextStep.length > 8, true, \\\"Next step exists\\\");\\nstrictEqual(after.history, \\\"Audit visible\\\", \\\"Customer-visible audit trail\\\");\\nstrictEqual(after.customerMessage.length > 12, true, \\\"Customer-safe message\\\");\\nstrictEqual(after.riskSummary, `${expectedSignals.length} signals: ${expectedSignals.map((item) => item.name).join(\\\", \\\")}`, \\\"Risk summary\\\");\\nstrictEqual(after.tasks, `${expectedOwners.length} owner tasks`, \\\"Owner task count\\\");\\nassertPersistedState(runData, expectedStatus, expectedOwners, expectedSignals);\\n\\nconsole.log(\\\"AST-Bench acceptance passed: strategic-account-rescue/postgres\\\");\\n\\nfunction assertPersistedState(tables, expectedStatus, expectedOwners, expectedSignals) {\\n  \\n  const request = tables.workflow_requests[0];\\n  const state = tables.workflow_state.find((item) => item.request_id === request.request_id);\\n  strictEqual(Boolean(state), true, \\\"Workflow state must be persisted\\\");\\n  strictEqual(state.status, expectedStatus, \\\"Persisted status\\\");\\n  const tasks = tables.owner_tasks.filter((item) => item.request_id === request.request_id);\\n  strictEqual(tasks.length, expectedOwners.length, \\\"Owner tasks persisted\\\");\\n  deepStrictEqual(tasks.map((item) => item.owner_group), expectedOwners, \\\"Task owner groups\\\");\\n  strictEqual(tasks.every((item) => item.title && item.due_at && item.status === \\\"open\\\"), true, \\\"Tasks have production fields\\\");\\n  strictEqual(tables.customer_messages.some((item) => item.request_id === request.request_id && item.body), true, \\\"Customer message persisted\\\");\\n  strictEqual(tables.audit_events.some((item) => item.request_id === request.request_id && item.customer_visible), true, \\\"Customer-visible audit event persisted\\\");\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### What the test demands (the implementation contract)\\n\\n`applyBenchmarkTask(db, now)` must mutate `db` (the tables object) in place AND return a portal view object. After it runs:\\n\\n**Returned object (`after`):**\\n- `after.status` === `\\\"At-risk escalation active with executive recovery owner routing and customer-visible audit history.\\\"` (the literal `expected_outcome` from the request).\\n- `after.owner` === owner groups sorted by `group_order`, joined with `\\\" + \\\"` → `\\\"Customer Success + Support + Finance + Executive Sponsor\\\"`.\\n- `after.nextStep.length > 8` (any non-trivial string).\\n- `after.history` === `\\\"Audit visible\\\"`.\\n- `after.customerMessage.length > 12`.\\n- `after.riskSummary` === `\\\"6 signals: strategic, account, rescue, enterprise account, open customer impact, audit required\\\"` (count + signal names sorted by `signal_order`).\\n- `after.tasks` === `\\\"4 owner tasks\\\"`.\\n\\n**Persisted state (mutations to `runData`):**\\n- `workflow_state`: push one row with `request_id` === the request's, and `status` === expectedStatus.\\n- `owner_tasks`: one row per owner group, in `group_order` order, each with truthy `title`, truthy `due_at`, and `status === \\\"open\\\"`, and `owner_group` matching.\\n- `customer_messages`: at least one row with matching `request_id` and truthy `body`.\\n- `audit_events`: at least one row with matching `request_id` and truthy `customer_visible`.\\n\\nCrucially, `after` must reflect persisted state — the cleanest implementation persists rows into the tables then calls `buildPortalView(db)` (which is what `portal-view.mjs` reads). `buildPortalView` derives `status` from `workflow_state.status`, `owner`/`tasks` from `owner_tasks`, `history` from an `audit_events` row with `customer_visible`, `customerMessage` from `customer_messages.body`, and `riskSummary` from `workflow_request_risk_signals` (already present in fixture). Note `buildPortalView` reads `state?.next_step` for `nextStep`, so the persisted `workflow_state` row should also carry a `next_step` (length > 8).\\n\\n## 6. Workflow / escalation / audit / risk source files\\n\\n- **`src/workflow.mjs`** — THE target file, currently a stub returning `buildPortalView(db)` with a TODO. Full content:\\n  ```js\\n  import { buildPortalView } from \\\"./portal-view.mjs\\\";\\n\\n  export function applyBenchmarkTask(db, now) {\\n    // TODO: Implement the benchmark workflow against the native data shape.\\n    return buildPortalView(db);\\n  }\\n  ```\\n- **`src/portal-view.mjs`** — read-only projection that both the test and render script rely on (reproduced/summarized in section 5). It is the contract for how persisted rows map to the portal view. Should not need changes.\\n- **`src/render-proof.mjs`** — `npm run render`; runs the workflow on a clone and writes `artifacts/before-after.json` and `.svg`. Not exercised by tests.\\n\\n## 7. Database setup / connection\\n\\nNone. There is no DB client, no connection string, no env var, no driver dependency. The \\\"database\\\" is `data/tables.json`, loaded synchronously in both the test and render script via:\\n```js\\nconst data = JSON.parse(readFileSync(new URL(\\\"../data/tables.json\\\", import.meta.url), \\\"utf8\\\"));\\n```\\nEach consumer `structuredClone`s it so the on-disk fixture is never mutated. `now` is a fixed timestamp `\\\"2026-06-18T12:00:00.000Z\\\"` passed in for determinism. The \\\"postgres\\\" vs other lanes is purely a naming/shape convention — the postgres lane uses normalized relational tables (requiring joins in code) vs. a document shape in other lanes.\\n\\n## 8. Seed / fixture data — `data/tables.json`\\n\\nSingle fixture file, loaded as described above. Key rows:\\n- `workflow_requests[0]`: `request_id` = `\\\"account-strategic-ac\\\"`, `title` = `\\\"Strategic account rescue\\\"`, `expected_outcome` = the exact expectedStatus string, `next_step` = `\\\"Customer Success owner review by 16:00\\\"`, plus a prewritten `customer_message`.\\n- `workflow_request_owner_groups`: 4 rows — Customer Success (1), Support (2), Finance (3), Executive Sponsor (4).\\n- `workflow_request_risk_signals`: 6 rows — strategic, account, rescue, enterprise account, open customer impact, audit required (orders 1–6).\\n- `accounts`, `account_contracts`, `contacts` (2), `activities` (6), `benchmark_fixture` (1): supporting context.\\n- `workflow_state`, `owner_tasks`, `audit_events`, `customer_messages`: all **empty arrays** — these are what the workflow must populate.\\n\\nI confirmed `npm test` currently FAILS at line 19 (status assertion: `'Needs work'` vs the expected escalation string), matching `tests-before.log`. The npm wrapper masks the real exit code (reports 0), but the underlying assertion throws.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Summary:** This is a zero-dependency Node ESM benchmark target with no real Postgres — the \\\"DB\\\" is `data/tables.json` (normalized tables), and the only file to implement is `src/workflow.mjs`, which must persist `workflow_state` (1 row, with status + next_step), `owner_tasks` (one `{owner_group, title, due_at, status:\\\"open\\\"}` per owner group in group_order), one `customer_messages` row (with `body`), and one `audit_events` row (with `customer_visible` truthy) into the passed-in tables, then return `buildPortalView(db)` so the seven `after.*` assertions in the unchangeable `tests/acceptance.test.mjs` pass.\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"stop_details\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":2,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":566,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":29542,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_token